{"author":{"id":"30a9cdd9e5369167dc36be4d3e5f98e516aa30b7571a17013bc815eef45f09c3"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1445439048,"nonce":"v9GUVaYnQkgan8CuiCmDBkwV42Y=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDU6SXNzdWUxMTI2MDcwMDM=","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/346","origin":"github"},"title":"RFC: JBrowse outputs","message":"Howdy all,\n\nI'm opening this up for input since I'm not happy with the system I've designed and need another pair of eyes on this.\n## Problem\n\nCurrently the JBrowse tool includes a complete copy of the JBrowse code as part of the output dataset. Great for reproducibility, horrific for user history sizes and for rsyncing `$galaxy_root/database`. \n\nMinifying JBrowse isn't working how I'd like it to (just yet) so short of that I'd like to attack this problem from another angle.\n\nJBrowse consists of a folder of HTML/JS/CSS, and _within_ that folder is a folder named \"data\" which contains all of the relevant files.\n\nThe perfect solution will:\n- detach jbrowse from the output, but retain it in downloads\n- retain similar level of usability, but clicking the eyeball to view in JBrowse should still work\n- retain ease of installation/use (i.e. just drop in as a tool in a workflow)\n## Options I've Dreamt Up\n\nThe best thing I've come up with is just outputting the \"data\" folder as a special jbrowse datatype. This would allow us to define a WebApollo and JBrowse GIE that make use of that folder. This achieves the detached jbrowse, but then fails on the usability unless y'all have ideas/suggestions here.\n\nMaybe I could create the datatype such that the HTML view of the datatype does magic and copies around a JBrowse file? Since no one else would be using this jbrowse datatype, I don't imagine it would be a problem, but that seems unnecessarily complex and I'm guessing will fail to download all the files properly.","files":null}]}